Project Description¶

For this project I am exploring publicly available data from LendingClub.com.
Lending Club connects people who need money (borrowers) with people who have money (investors).
Hopefully, as an investor you would want to invest in people who showed a profile of having a high probability of paying you back. We will try to create a model that will help predict this.

Check out more info on Lending Club on Wikipedia. Lending Club also had a very interesting year in 2016.

This dataset is from before they went public.

I am using lending data from 2007-2010 and will try to classify and predict whether or not the borrower paid back their loan in full. You will analyze the data file provided.

Here are what the columns represent:

  • credit.policy: 1 if the customer meets the credit underwriting criteria of LendingClub.com, and 0 otherwise.
  • purpose: The purpose of the loan (takes values "credit_card", "debt_consolidation", "educational", "major_purchase", "small_business", and "all_other").
  • int.rate: The interest rate of the loan, as a proportion (a rate of 11% would be stored as 0.11). Borrowers judged by LendingClub.com to be more risky are assigned higher interest rates.
  • installment: The monthly installments owed by the borrower if the loan is funded.
  • log.annual.inc: The natural log of the self-reported annual income of the borrower.
  • dti: The debt-to-income ratio of the borrower (amount of debt divided by annual income).
  • fico: The FICO credit score of the borrower.
  • days.with.cr.line: The number of days the borrower has had a credit line.
  • revol.bal: The borrower's revolving balance (amount unpaid at the end of the credit card billing cycle).
  • revol.util: The borrower's revolving line utilization rate (the amount of the credit line used relative to total credit available).
  • inq.last.6mths: The borrower's number of inquiries by creditors in the last 6 months.
  • delinq.2yrs: The number of times the borrower had been 30+ days past due on a payment in the past 2 years.
  • pub.rec: The borrower's number of derogatory public records (bankruptcy filings, tax liens, or judgments).
  • not.fully.paid: Whether the loan was paid back or not.

# Assuming you have a DataFrame named 'df' with columns 'FICO' and 'credit.policy'

# Separate FICO scores based on credit.policy outcome
fico_1 = loans[loans['credit.policy'] == 1]['fico']
fico_0 = loans[loans['credit.policy'] == 0]['fico']

# Set up the histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plot histogram for credit.policy == 1
plt.hist(fico_1, bins=30, alpha=0.5, color='blue', label='Credit Policy: 1')

# Plot histogram for credit.policy == 0
plt.hist(fico_0, bins=30, alpha=0.5, color='red', label='Credit Policy: 0')

# Add labels and title

plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Distribution of FICO Scores by Credit Policy')

# Show plot
plt.show()

Decision Tree Model¶

Implementing the model . Finding Accuracies for both train and validation

In [78]:
# Import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
In [79]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report,balanced_accuracy_score

# Initiate the Decision Tree classifier with default parameters
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier()

# Fit the model on the training data
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the training and validation sets
y_train_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
y_val_pred = clf.predict(X_val)
#print(len(X_test))
# Calculate accuracy score for training and validation sets
train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_train_pred)
val_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_val, y_val_pred)

print("Training Accuracy:", train_accuracy)
print("Validation Accuracy:", val_accuracy)

# Create confusion matrix for validation set
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_val, y_val_pred)
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)

# Provide performance metrics for the validation set
#print("Classification Report:")
#print(classification_report(y_test, y_val_pred))
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

# Get the classification report
report = classification_report(y_val, y_val_pred, output_dict=True)

# Extract precision, recall, and F1-score for each class
precision = report['macro avg']['precision']
recall = report['macro avg']['recall']
f1_score = report['macro avg']['f1-score']
tn = conf_matrix[0][0]
fn = conf_matrix[1][0]
specificity = tn / (tn+fn)
balance = balanced_accuracy_score(y_val, y_val_pred)

print("Precision:", precision)
print("Recall:", recall)
print("F1-score:", f1_score)
print("specificity",specificity)
print("balanced accuracy",balance)

i) Using the training data perform hyper-parameter tuning.

ii) Trying with several values for the min_samples_split hyper-parameter and applying cross validation (GridSearchCV) to finding the best value.

iii) Using the best model to provide the performance metrics for the validation set.

iv) Trying several values for the max_depth hyper-parameter and applying cross validation (GridSearchCV) to finding the best value.

v) Using the best model provide the performance metrics for the validation set.

vi) Performing grid search (GridSearchCV) to check min_samples_split and max_depth.

vii) Using the best model provide the performance metrics for the validation set.

In [80]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Hyperparameter tuning for min_samples_split
param_grid = {'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10, 15, 20]}

grid_search_min_samples_split = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeClassifier(), param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=5)
grid_search_min_samples_split.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best min_samples_split:", grid_search_min_samples_split.best_params_)

# Evaluate the best model's performance on the validation set
best_clf_min_samples_split = grid_search_min_samples_split.best_estimator_
y_pred_val_min_samples_split = best_clf_min_samples_split.predict(X_val)

print("Performance metrics for min_samples_split:")
print(classification_report(y_val, y_pred_val_min_samples_split))

# Hyperparameter tuning for max_depth
param_grid = {'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 15, 20]}

grid_search_max_depth = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeClassifier(), param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=5)
grid_search_max_depth.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best max_depth:", grid_search_max_depth.best_params_)

# Evaluate the best model's performance on the validation set
best_clf_max_depth = grid_search_max_depth.best_estimator_
y_pred_val_max_depth = best_clf_max_depth.predict(X_val)

print("Performance metrics for max_depth:")
print(classification_report(y_val, y_pred_val_max_depth))

# Perform grid search for both min_samples_split and max_depth
param_grid = {'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10, 15, 20],
              'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 15, 20]}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeClassifier(), param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

# Evaluate the best model's performance on the validation set
best_clf = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_val = best_clf.predict(X_val)

print("Performance metrics for the best model:")
print(classification_report(y_val, y_pred_val))

if len(feature_names) != len(feature_importances):

Using the training data perform hyper-parameter tuning.

  • Perform grid search (GridSearchCV) where you check for min_samples_split, max_depth, and n_estimators.

  • Using the best model provide the performance metrics for the validation set.

In [84]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 20],
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200]
}

# Initiate the Random Forest classifier
clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Perform grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(clf, param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the best model
best_clf = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Make predictions on the validation set
y_val_pred = best_clf.predict(X_val)
print("Best parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

# Calculate performance metrics for the validation set
print("Performance metrics for the best model:")
print(classification_report(y_val, y_val_pred))

importance_df = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': feature_names, 'Importance': feature_importances})

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report,balanced_accuracy_score

# Initiate the Decision Tree classifier with default parameters
clf = AdaBoostClassifier()

# Fit the model on the training data
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the training and validation sets
y_train_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
y_val_pred = clf.predict(X_val)
#print(len(X_test))
# Calculate accuracy score for training and validation sets
train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_train_pred)
val_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_val, y_val_pred)

print("Training Accuracy:", train_accuracy)
print("Validation Accuracy:", val_accuracy)

# Create confusion matrix for validation set
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_val, y_val_pred)
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)

# Provide performance metrics for the validation set
#print("Classification Report:")
#print(classification_report(y_test, y_val_pred))
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

# Get the classification report
report = classification_report(y_val, y_val_pred, output_dict=True)

# Extract precision, recall, and F1-score for each class
precision = report['macro avg']['precision']
recall = report['macro avg']['recall']
f1_score = report['macro avg']['f1-score']
tn = conf_matrix[0][0]
fn = conf_matrix[1][0]
specificity = tn / (tn+fn)
balance = balanced_accuracy_score(y_val, y_val_pred)

print("Precision:", precision)
print("Recall:", recall)
print("F1-score:", f1_score)
print("specificity",specificity)
print("balanced accuracy",balance)

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.5, 1.0],
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200]
}

# Initiate the AdaBoost classifier
clf = AdaBoostClassifier()

# Perform grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(clf, param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the best model
best_clf = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Make predictions on the validation set
y_val_pred = best_clf.predict(X_val)
print("Best parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

# Calculate performance metrics for the validation set
print("Performance metrics for the best model:")
print(classification_report(y_val, y_val_pred))

In [97]:
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier
########## Level 0 models ##########
rf = GradientBoostingClassifier()
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier()
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
dt.fit(X_train, y_train)
rf_train_preds = rf.predict(X_train)
dt_train_preds = dt.predict(X_train)
X_stack_train = np.c_[rf_train_preds, dt_train_preds]
########## Fit level 1 model on stacked train features ##########
lr = RandomForestClassifier()
lr.fit(X_stack_train, y_train)

rf_test_preds = rf.predict(X_test)
dt_test_preds = dt.predict(X_test)

X_stack_test = np.c_[rf_test_preds, dt_test_preds]
y_pred = lr.predict(X_stack_test)
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score
f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"F1-score: {f1:.4f}")

F1-score: 0.5709

In [98]:
from sklearn.metrics import recall_score
In [100]:
best_decision_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=10, min_samples_split=5)
best_random_forest = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=10, min_samples_split=10, random_state=42)
best_adaboost = AdaBoostClassifier(learning_rate=0.1, n_estimators=200)
best_gradient_boosting = GradientBoostingClassifier(learning_rate=0.05,n_estimators=100)
models = {
    "Decision Tree"    : best_decision_tree,
    "Random Forest"    : best_random_forest,
    "AdaBoost"         : best_adaboost,
    "Gradient Boosting": best_gradient_boosting
}
results = []
for model_name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    #precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    results.append({
        "Model": model_name,
        "Confusion Matrix": cm,
        "Accuracy": accuracy,
        "Recall": recall,
        "Precision": precision
    })
print("Summary of Results on Test Set:")
print("Model\t\tAccuracy\tRecall\t\tPrecision")
for result in results:
    print(f"{result['Model']}\t{result['Accuracy']:.4f}\t\t{result['Recall']:.4f}\t\t{result['Precision']:.4f}")
